'''Mishima Shrine''' (三島神社) is a {{ill|Shrine|ja|神社}} located in 3‑chome, {{ill|Shimotani|ja|下谷}}, {{ill|Taito Ward|ja|台東区}}, {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京都}}. Its head shrine is the {{ill|Ooyamatsumi Shrine|ja|大山祇神社}} in Imabari, {{ill|Ehime Prefecture|ja|愛媛県}}—situated in the Ichinomiya of {{ill|Iyo Province|ja|伊予国}}—which is revered as Japan’s National Guardian Shrine.

== Enshrined Deities ==
* Main Deity  
** {{ill|Ooyamatsumi|ja|オオヤマツミ|lt=Ooyamatsumi|lt_ja=大山祇命}}
* Auxiliary Deities  
** {{ill|Watasuhiko|ja|和足彦神}}  
** {{ill|Mihajimahime|ja|身島姫神}}  
** {{ill|Kami-tsuhime|ja|上津姫命|lt=Thunder God|lt_ja=雷神}}  
** {{ill|Shimo-tsuhime|ja|下津姫命|lt=Dragon God|lt_ja=龍神}}  
Kami‑tsuhime is identified with {{ill|Iwanagahime|ja|イワナガヒメ|lt=Iwanagahime|lt_ja=磐長姫命}}, and Shimo‑tsuhime is identified with {{ill|Konohananosakuyahime|ja|コノハナノサクヤビメ|lt=Konohananosakuyahime|lt_ja=木花咲耶姫命}}.

== History ==
In the 4th year of {{ill|Kōan|ja|弘安}} ({{ill|1281|ja|1281st year }}), {{ill|Kōno Michiyuki|ja|河野通有}} set out to pray for victory in the {{ill|Mongol Invasion|ja|元寇}} by appealing to his tutelary deity, Mishima Daimyojin ({{ill|Ooyamatsumi Shrine|ja|大山祇神社}}). Under the guidance of the white heron—the divine messenger ({{ill|Divine Messenger|ja|神使}}) of Mishima Daimyojin—he achieved remarkable military exploits. Upon his return, he received in a dream the divine command to enshrine Mishima Daimyojin in the {{ill|Musashi Province|ja|武蔵国}}’s {{ill|Toyoshima District|ja|豊島郡 (武蔵国)|lt=Toyoshima District|lt_ja=豊島郡}}, and it is said that he subsequently enshrined the deity at the residence of the Kōno clan within Ueno Mountain ({{ill|Ueno Mountain|ja|上野恩賜公園|lt=Ueno Mountain|lt_ja=上野山}}).

In the 3rd year of {{ill|Keian|ja|慶安}} ({{ill|1650|ja|1650th year }}), he was ordered by {{ill|Tokugawa Iemitsu|ja|徳川家光}} to relocate the shrine, and it was moved to Kanasusimura in Taito Ward (presently in {{ill|Negishi|ja|根岸 (台東区)|lt=Negishi|lt_ja=根岸}}). Furthermore, in the 7th year of {{ill|Hōei|ja|宝永}} ({{ill|1710|ja|1710th year }}), when the shrine grounds became property of the shogunate, it was relocated to Asakusa Koayacho (currently in {{ill|Kotobukicho|ja|寿 (台東区)|lt=Kotobukicho|lt_ja=寿}})—namely, the head shrine, Head Shrine Mishima Shrine, in Shijō‑chō of Kotobukicho. However, as the tutelary deity was too distant, a branch spirit was enshrined at the Hiyoke Inari Shrine site in Kanasukimachi of Kanasusimura. This branch is known as the Mishima Shrine of Kanasukimachi (Shimotani). To this day, the successive head priests of this shrine have been descendants of Kōno Michiyuki.

In addition, parishioners in Negishi of Kanasusimura also enshrined a branch spirit from the head shrine and co-enshrined it at Kumano Shrine; this is the Former Mishima Shrine of Negishi 1‑chome.

== Shrine Grounds ==
* **Hiyoke Inari Shrine** – A subsidiary shrine ({{ill|Setsusha|ja|摂末社|lt=Setsusha|lt_ja=摂社}}) within the grounds, serving as the land deity ({{ill|Land Deity|ja|地主神}}) of Mishima Shrine. Its date of establishment is unknown, but it is said that the Tokugawa clan built it within Ueno Mountain for protection against fires. In ancient times, it was known as “Misaki Inari.” Later, as the area was designated as a {{ill|Fire Protection Zone|ja|火除地}}, it came to be known as “Hiyoke Inari” and has since been venerated for its powers to ward off fires, bring prosperity in business, ensure family safety, prevent disasters, and secure overall safety.
