{{Shrine
|Name=Mishima Shrine
|画像={{ill|File:三島神社(下谷).jpg|ja|三島神社(下谷).jpg|lt=250px|lt_ja=250px}}
|所在地=Tokyo, Taito Ward, Shimotani 3-chome, 7-5, ({{sfn|東京都神社庁}})
|祭神={{ill|Ooyamatsumi|ja|オオヤマツミ|1=Ōyamatsumi|lt=Ooyamatsumi|lt_ja=大山祇命|12=draft}}{{sfn|東京都神社庁}}
|社格=Village Shrine
|創建={{ill|Kōan|ja|弘安|12=draft}}4th year （{{ill|1281|ja|1281st year|12=draft}}）
|例祭={{ill|June 14|ja|6月14日|12=draft}}・{{ill|June 15|ja|6月15日|lt=15|lt_ja=15日|12=draft}} on the Saturday and Sunday nearest these dates
}}

'''Mishima Shrine''' (三島神社) is a {{ill|Shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in 3‑chome, {{ill|Shimotani|ja|下谷|12=draft}}, {{ill|Taito Ward|ja|台東区|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京都|12=draft}}. Its head shrine is the {{ill|Ooyamatsumi Shrine|ja|大山祇神社|12=draft}} in Imabari, {{ill|Ehime Prefecture|ja|愛媛県|12=draft}}—situated in the Ichinomiya of {{ill|Iyo Province|ja|伊予国|12=draft}}—which is revered as Japan’s National Guardian Shrine.

== Enshrined Deities ==
* Main Deity  
** {{ill|Ooyamatsumi|ja|オオヤマツミ|1=Ōyamatsumi|lt=Ooyamatsumi|lt_ja=大山祇命|12=draft}}
* Auxiliary Deities  
** {{ill|Watasuhiko|ja|和足彦神|12=draft}}  
** {{ill|Mihajimahime|ja|身島姫神|12=draft}}  
** {{ill|Kami-tsuhime|ja|上津姫命|lt=Thunder God|lt_ja=雷神|12=draft}}  
** {{ill|Shimo-tsuhime|ja|下津姫命|lt=Dragon God|lt_ja=龍神|12=draft}}  
Kami‑tsuhime is identified with {{ill|Iwanagahime|ja|イワナガヒメ|1=Iwanaga-hime|lt=Iwanagahime|lt_ja=磐長姫命|12=draft}}, and Shimo‑tsuhime is identified with {{ill|Konohananosakuyahime|ja|コノハナノサクヤビメ|lt=Konohananosakuyahime|lt_ja=木花咲耶姫命|12=draft}}.

== History ==
In the 4th year of {{ill|Kōan|ja|弘安|12=draft}} ({{ill|1281|ja|1281st year|12=draft}}), {{ill|Kōno Michiyuki|ja|河野通有|12=draft}} set out to pray for victory in the {{ill|Mongol Invasion|ja|元寇|12=draft}} by appealing to his tutelary deity, Mishima Daimyojin ({{ill|Ooyamatsumi Shrine|ja|大山祇神社|12=draft}}). Under the guidance of the white heron—the divine messenger ({{ill|Divine Messenger|ja|神使|12=draft}}) of Mishima Daimyojin—he achieved remarkable military exploits. Upon his return, he received in a dream the divine command to enshrine Mishima Daimyojin in the {{ill|Musashi Province|ja|武蔵国|12=draft}}’s {{ill|Toyoshima District|ja|豊島郡 (武蔵国)|lt=Toyoshima District|lt_ja=豊島郡|12=draft}}, and it is said that he subsequently enshrined the deity at the residence of the Kōno clan within Ueno Mountain ({{ill|Ueno Mountain|ja|上野恩賜公園|lt=Ueno Mountain|lt_ja=上野山|12=draft}}).

In the 3rd year of {{ill|Keian|ja|慶安|12=draft}} ({{ill|1650|ja|1650th year|12=draft}}), he was ordered by {{ill|Tokugawa Iemitsu|ja|徳川家光|12=draft}} to relocate the shrine, and it was moved to Kanasusimura in Taito Ward (presently in {{ill|Negishi|ja|根岸 (台東区)|lt=Negishi|lt_ja=根岸|12=draft}}). Furthermore, in the 7th year of {{ill|Hōei|ja|宝永|12=draft}} ({{ill|1710|ja|1710th year|12=draft}}), when the shrine grounds became property of the shogunate, it was relocated to Asakusa Koayacho (currently in {{ill|Kotobukicho|ja|寿 (台東区)|lt=Kotobukicho|lt_ja=寿|12=draft}})—namely, the head shrine, Head Shrine Mishima Shrine, in Shijō‑chō of Kotobukicho. However, as the tutelary deity was too distant, a branch spirit was enshrined at the Hiyoke Inari Shrine site in Kanasukimachi of Kanasusimura. This branch is known as the Mishima Shrine of Kanasukimachi (Shimotani). To this day, the successive head priests of this shrine have been descendants of Kōno Michiyuki.

In addition, parishioners in Negishi of Kanasusimura also enshrined a branch spirit from the head shrine and co-enshrined it at Kumano Shrine; this is the Former Mishima Shrine of Negishi 1‑chome.

== Shrine Grounds ==
* **Hiyoke Inari Shrine** – A subsidiary shrine ({{ill|Setsusha|ja|摂末社|lt=Setsusha|lt_ja=摂社|12=draft}}) within the grounds, serving as the land deity ({{ill|Land Deity|ja|地主神|12=draft}}) of Mishima Shrine. Its date of establishment is unknown, but it is said that the Tokugawa clan built it within Ueno Mountain for protection against fires. In ancient times, it was known as “Misaki Inari.” Later, as the area was designated as a {{ill|Fire Protection Zone|ja|火除地|12=draft}}, it came to be known as “Hiyoke Inari” and has since been venerated for its powers to ward off fires, bring prosperity in business, ensure family safety, prevent disasters, and secure overall safety.
* **Raijin Well** – In old Musashino, where lightning was frequent and greatly feared by the locals, lightning once struck Mishima Shrine. The priest sealed the lightning in a well. When the lightning implored, “Release me from the well,” the priest granted its request on the condition that it never strike the area again. It is said that lightning has not struck here since, and the well is revered as a talisman against lightning.
* **Mishima Shrine Hana‑hyō Monument** – A monument inscribed by {{ill|Ozaki Yukio|ja|尾崎行雄|lt=Ozaki Kyūdō|lt_ja=尾崎咢堂|12=draft}} during his tenure as Mayor of Tokyo.
* **Survey Point** – A surveying marker established in the early Meiji era by the Geographic Division of the {{ill|Ministry of Home Affairs|ja|内務省 (日本)|lt=Ministry of Home Affairs|lt_ja=内務省|12=draft}}, marked by an inscription of “Fu” on the paving stone at the north gate entrance.
* Saplings of the {{ill|Miharu Takizakura|ja|三春滝桜|12=draft}} in {{ill|Miharu Town|ja|三春町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Fukushima Prefecture|ja|福島県|12=draft}}.

== Reconstruction Plan ==
In proceeding with the reconstruction of the aging shrine buildings, a portion of the property will be subject to a fixed‑term land lease ({{ill|Fixed-term Land Lease|ja|定期借地権|12=draft}}) until {{ill|2099|ja|2099th year|12=draft}},<ref name="tatekae1">{{cite web |title=Mitsui Fudosan’s Integrated Development Condominium with Shrine in Iriyatani |author= |agency=|publisher=Real Estate Distribution Research Institute|url=https://www.re-port.net/article/news/0000077259/|date=2024-11-11|accessdate=2025-2-2}}</ref> and {{ill|Mitsui Fudosan Residential|ja|三井不動産レジデンシャル|12=draft}} is developing a condominium ({{ill|Condominium|ja|マンション|12=draft}}). Furthermore, there is an initiative to repurpose some of the roof tiles ({{ill|Roof Tile|ja|瓦|12=draft}}) and lanterns ({{ill|Lantern|ja|灯篭|12=draft}}) used before reconstruction as common materials or art in the condominium.<ref name="tatekae2">{{cite web |title=Notice of Scheduled Completion of Mishima Shrine Reconstruction|author= |agency=|publisher=Mishima Shrine|url=https://www.mishimajinjya.or.jp/wp/%E4%B8%89%E5%B3%B6%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE%E5%86%8D%E7%94%9F%E8%A8%88%E7%94%BB/%E4%B8%89%E5%B3%B6%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE%E5%BB%BA%E6%9B%BF%E3%81%88%E5%AE%8C%E6%88%90%E4%BA%88%E5%AE%9A%E3%81%AE%E3%81%94%E6%A1%88%E5%86%85/|date=|accessdate=2025-2-2}}</ref> Overall completion is scheduled around August in the 8th year of Reiwa ({{ill|2026|ja|2026th year|12=draft}}).

